\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 young.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
The various techniques used to build these nests are so perfect that one would not expect them from animals devoid of intellect and technological skills. As the following pages will show in great detail, they could not have been designed by the anim
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
als themselves, because they would have to plan out the many stages of the project before even beginning to build. First off, they'd have to realize the need for a nest for the safety of their eggs and young. Next, they'd need to locate the most suitable 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 p\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 lace for their nests, since no creature builds its nest just anywhere.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Building materials used in the nest's construction are carefully selected from those available in the enviro\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
nment. For example, water birds build nests from plant matter that will float, in case of unexpected flooding. Birds living among reeds, on the other hand, make their nests wide and deep, to prevent their eggs from falling out when the reeds bend in the w
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
nd. Birds inhabiting deserts build their nests atop of shrubs and cacti, where the temperature is 10o C (50o F) lower than on ground level, where the oven-like 45o C (113o F) heat would kill the young birds in a very short time. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Choosing the right locatio\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n for a nest requires knowledge as well as intelligence. An animal cannot foresee the risks of flooding, or the danger that high temperatures pose for young birds\hich\f0 
\emdash \loch\f0 much less how to prevent their adverse effects. We are faced, then, with a paradox: On the o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e hand, animals of little intelligence and no knowledge and, on the other, behavior that is conscious, intelligent and knowledgeable. God is the owner of consciousness, intelligence, and knowledge; and expresses these qualities in His perfect creations.

\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Th\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
e healthy survival of their offspring is vitally important for all living species; and from the moment of laying their eggs or giving birth to their young, protecting them becomes the parents' sole occupation. The penduline tit, paying utmost attention to
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
the safety of its offspring, builds a number of dummy nests in the vicinity of its real nest, to divert the attention of any hungry enemy. This diversion strategy, obviously the result of careful planning, couldn't possibly be the product of the penduline
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 tit's own intellect. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
One of the most common methods birds use to protect a nest from predators is to build it in a thorny bush or camouflage it among dry leaves. Some species, in order to protect the female and her eggs, wall off the entrance to their nes
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t structure with mud while she is inside, or else mix their saliva with soil to form a sort of mortar they use to build a wall covering the entrance.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 These can hardly be skills those animals could develop on their own. What, then, enables these birds and o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ther animals to build nests so intricate and perfectly designed? How do animals acquire these skills?
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Another detail should not be disregarded. At birth, every animal possesses the knowledge of building its characteristic nest. Every member of that species\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
, wherever on Earth it might be, builds its nest in the same way. This clearly shows that creatures did not learn their nest-building methods or acquire them in any casual sort of way, but that this knowledge and skill was given them by the same power. Go
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 d\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , the All-knowing and All-powerful, creates them together with their skills and gives them this knowledge.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Quite aside from their architectural perfection, the extraordinary dedication that parents invest in building their nests is certainly worth noticing\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
. Whereas birds build ordinary nests for themselves, they build ones for their offspring with the utmost care. Considering the different phases involved in nest building, we can better understand the scale of the efforts birds put into it, the energy they
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
invest and the selflessness of their behavior. To build its nest, a bird can carry only a few twigs or grass stalks at a time in its beak, and so must make hundreds of flights to gather the building materials it requires. But this does not discourage the 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 b\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ird. It continues to forage patiently. It never becomes frustrated, never settles for less, is never too tired or lazy to complete its nest in every last detail.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 According to Darwin's natural selection theory, these animals should be concerned only with th\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
emselves. In an environment where only the fittest and strongest could succeed in the battle for survival, would animals exhaust themselves so that their vulnerable offspring could survive? What could explain their preparing in advance a secure environmen
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 for the arrival of their vulnerable young? Natural selection cannot answer these questions; neither can the theory of evolution, nor any other atheist ideology. These questions have one answer only: God gives to these animals dedication, patience, endura
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ce, persistence and ambition. God instills them with these qualities so that the strong can protect the weak, so that natural balances can continue and these species can exist until their appointed times and can become living signs of God's artistry, powe
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 , wisdom and the superiority of His creation.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Subsequent pages will give examples of animals renowned for their architectural and decorative skills. Eggs and later on, the young birds that hatch from them are vulnerable in the extreme, and especially in ne
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ed of protection. Therefore, God directs their parents to build them exactly the right type of nests.
