\f0\fs28\insrsid9665616\charrsid13781270 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Selfless Devotion in Ant Colonies
\par }\pard\plain \qj \fi567\li0\ri170\sl-320\slmult0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin170\lin0\itap0\pararsid10365038 \fs24\lang1033\langfe2052\loch\af8\hich\af8\dbch\af13\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp2052 {\f0\fs22\insrsid9665616\charrsid10365038 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
1. One striking aspects of colony life is that all ants share food. If two ants from the same colony meet, one hungry and the other with a belly full of digested or semi-digested food, the hungry ant will ask the other one to share some. This kind of requ
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 st is never turned down. Ants also feed their larvae from the food in their stomachs and often, end up keeping less for themselves than what they offer to others.133}{\f0\fs22\insrsid10365038 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  }{\f0\fs22\insrsid9665616\charrsid10365038 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2. In ant colonies, there is perfect sharing of tasks, and each ant fulfills its responsi\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
bility with great devotion. The responsibility of the "soldier ant" is to guard the entrance to the nest. It will admit only ants belonging to its colony and refuse entrance to all others. The heads of these guard ants serve as a living "gate" to the nest
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 .\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  They guard the entrance all day and never leaving it unattended.134 In the case of an attack, these ants form the first line of defense.}{\f0\fs22\insrsid10365038 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  }{
\f0\fs22\insrsid9665616\charrsid10365038 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 3. Along with sharing food, ants will also share, with as many other ants they can, information about the location of\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 food sources. In their behavior, there is no sign of selfish struggle. The ant who discovers a new source of food eats her fill and then returns to the nest, leaving behind a chemical trail on the way by touching her lower abdomen to the ground at regula
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  intervals. Also, she goes around the nest three to six times, speedily communicating the news to the other ants and on returning to the source of food, is accompanied by many others.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  4. Medium-sized workers in a colony of leaf-cutting ants spend their wh\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ole day transporting leaves. During this time, they are exposed and highly vulnerable to attacks, especially from a species of fly that deposits its eggs onto the ants' heads. The maggots hatching from these eggs will feed on the ant's head and decapitate
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
it by eating into its brain. When carrying leaves, worker ants are defenseless against these flies, but other ants will fight back for them. Smaller ants from the same colony take up positions on the leaves being carried back to the nest and fight off the
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e predatory flies.135}{\f0\fs22\insrsid10365038 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  }{\f0\fs22\insrsid9665616\charrsid10365038 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
5. Some ants feed on the highly sugary digestive wastes of aphids, which is why they are known as honey ants. They carry this sugary substance they extract from the aphids to their nest, where they store it using a very original meth
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
od. A few of the worker ants serve as living storage tanks. Ants returning to their nest regurgitate the food into their mouths, and those ants store it in their lower abdomens, which can inflate to the size of blueberries.136 Each chamber contains betwee
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  25 to 30 of them, each dangling from the ceiling, where she remains immobile. Should one of them fall to the ground, the other ants will return her to her original position. 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 These living storage tanks can hold up to eight times the original mass of the a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
nt. During winters or droughts, hungry ants visit them to feed. The hungry insect puts her mouth into the mouth of the "storage" ant which, by contracting the muscles around her lower abdomen, delivers a drop of nectar to the visitor. These ants couldn't 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 p\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ossibly have developed such a method of storing food on their own. Those that serve as living honey jars clearly demonstrate their selfless devotion, by remaining suspended upside down from the ceiling, carrying eight times their own body weight, expectin
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 g\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 nothing in return. Patiently they help to feed other ants of the colony, one by one. Clearly, these ants' system and the physical capabilities that make it possible couldn't be the results of chance. In each generation of honey ants, a few take it upon t
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 emselves to serve in this way, which proves that all of them act on the inspiration of their Lord God.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 6. One method that ants use to defend their colony is to commit suicide. They can deliver their kamikaze attacks against an enemy in a variety of ways. O\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ne of the most interesting examples is provided by a species living in the rainforests of Malaysia. This ant has a venom gland stretching from its jaw towards the back of its body. If confronted by an enemy, the ant contracts its abdominal muscles so forc
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 fully that the gland and surrounding tissues burst, spraying the enemy with its poison before it dies.137}{\f0\fs22\insrsid10365038 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  }{
\f0\fs22\insrsid9665616\charrsid10365038 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 7. In order to reproduce, male and female ants must be very dedicated. Soon after their mating flight, the winged male ants expire. The female looks \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
for a suitable place to build her nest and when she finds one, will enter it and break off her wings. Then she seals off the entrance and remains inside without food for weeks, even months, all alone. Later she will lay her first eggs as a queen ant. The 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
nly things she will have eaten in all this time are her own wings. The very first larvae that emerge she feeds with her saliva. This is a period of great devotion for the queen ant, in beginning a new colony.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 8. If their nest is attacked and occupied, the \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ants move to protect their brood at any cost. The soldier ants move to the area under attack to fight the invaders, while workers rush to the nursery chambers, evacuating the larvae and young ants between their jaws. They carry them outside the nest and h
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 i\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
de them somewhere safe until the attack has been fought off.138 It would be expected for a creature like the ant to be concerned only with itself, seeking a place to hide. But the worker ants, soldiers and those guarding the entrance aren't concerned abou
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  their own lives and will die for one another if necessary. This is selfless devotion at the highest level, and all ants have been behaving in this way for millions of years.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Thus far, we have related astonishing behavior in the animal kingdom, but still n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
eed to point out that the creatures acting in these surprising ways are tiny ants. These insects are no importance to those who are used to seeing them every day. But when we observe them carefully, we see the intelligence inherent in their behavior is to
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 significant to be ignored. With their little brains that cannot be seen by the naked eye, consisting of so few nerve cells, they perform intelligent actions that wouldn't be expected of them. For millions of years, they have been obeying their Creator Go
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 d\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 's orders in great discipline and without fail. They have surrendered to Him and move only by His will. All beings submit to God like the ants. As the Qur'an says:
